        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(usage): bound WHAM probe rate-limit response body to prevent OOM",
        "body": "## What\n\nBound the WHAM rate-limit probe response body in `src/agents/auth-profiles/usage.ts` to prevent an unbounded memory allocation from a hostile or misconfigured endpoint.\n\n## Why\n\n`probeWhamForCooldown` calls an external rate-limit endpoint and reads the response with a bare `await res.json()`. Error-path branches already return early before reading the body, but the happy-path had no size guard — an adversarial server could stream an arbitrarily large body and exhaust heap.\n\n## How\n\nReplace the bare `res.json()` call with `readResponseWithLimit` (1 MiB cap, fail-closed). Parse the bounded buffer with `JSON.parse(new TextDecoder().decode(rawBody))`.\n\n## Evidence\n\n**Focused tests — real loopback HTTP server (no mocks):**\n\n```\n✓ WHAM usage response body limit (real loopback HTTP server) > rejects a response body exceeding 1 MiB (over-cap)   78ms\n✓ WHAM usage response body limit (real loopback HTTP server) > returns a parseable buffer for a normal JSON body (under-cap)   29ms\n```\n\n- **over-cap**: `node:http` server streams >1 MiB body without `Content-Length` → `readResponseWithLimit` rejects with `WHAM usage response too large`\n- **under-cap**: server returns a normal rate-limit JSON object → buffer parsed successfully as `WhamUsageResponse`\n- **mutation**: reverting to bare `res.json()` causes the over-cap test to fail — the guard is load-bearing\n\nAll 75 existing tests pass unchanged.\n\n## Compatibility\n\nFail-closed on responses over 1 MiB. WHAM usage payloads are a small JSON object (rate-limit metadata); 1 MiB provides ≥1000× headroom over any legitimate payload.\n\n## Security & Privacy\n\nNo secrets or PII involved. Improves robustness against hostile external endpoints.",
